context: <b4_0>The Appalachian Mountains<b4_0/> (i/ˌæpəˈleɪʃᵻn/ or /ˌæpəˈlætʃᵻn/,[note 1] <b6_0>French<b6_0/>: <a0_0>les Appalaches<a0_0/>), often called the Appalachians, are <a1_0>a system of mountains in eastern North America<a1_0/>. The Appalachians first formed <a2_0>roughly <b5_0>480 million years ago<b5_0/><a2_0/> during the <a3_0><b8_0>Ordovician Period<b8_0/><a3_0/> and once reached elevations similar to those of the Alps and the Rocky Mountains before they were eroded. The Appalachian chain is a barrier to <b7_0>east-west travel<b7_0/> as it forms a series of alternating ridgelines and valleys oriented in opposition to any road running east-west.
